`gdx-controllers` extension have its Ouya button and axis codes declared as `public static final`, but their initialization is done inside a `static` block which makes them non constant expression. Their values are set at runtime after the first access to any of the class members.

That makes writing `switch` statements end with a `case expressions must be constant expression` compile error. Like so:

```
    @Override
    public boolean buttonDown(final Controller controller, final int buttonCode) {
        switch (buttonCode) {
        case Ouya.BUTTON_O:  // This line won't compile
            // Do something
            break;
            // ...
        }
        // ...
    }
```

Any reason behind this decision? I believe all the input listeners logic is better handled this way, as I have already done in the past using `Input.Keys`.

